<p>Let's suppose I write this class:</p>  <pre><code>public A&lt;T&gt; : T { } </code></pre>  <p>Basically, I want <code>A</code> to extend from (inherit) whatever <code>T</code> is.</p>  <p>For instance, if I have this:</p>  <pre><code>public class B {      public string Name { get { return "B"; } } } </code></pre>  <p>I should be able to accomplish something like this:</p>  <pre><code>B instance = new A&lt;B&gt;(); Console.WriteLine(instance.Name); </code></pre>  <p>which doesn't compile.</p>  <p>How can I extend from a generic argument?</p>  <p>If it can't be done, why is it not possible?</p>